Let S be a <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu14" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=388" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 14)" >semigroup</a>. An <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu13" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=2604" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 13)" >idempotent</a> eS is <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu12" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=6153" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 12)" >primitive</a> if for every other idempotent <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu11" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=3264" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 11)" >fS</a> , ef=fe=f=0e=f

A semigroup S (without <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu10" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=10602" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 10)" >zero</a>) is <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu9" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=6153" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 9)" >completely simple</a> if it is <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu8" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=5905" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 8)" >simple</a> and <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu7" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=1635" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 7)" >contains</a> a primitive idempotent.

A semigroup S is completely 0 -simple if it is 0 -simple and contains a primitive idempotent.

Completely simple and completely 0 -<a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu6" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=3521" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 6)" >simple semigroups</a> maybe characterised by the Rees <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu5" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=4492" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 5)" >Theorem</a> ([Ho95], Theorem 3.2.3).

Note:

A semigroup (without zero) is completely simple if and only if it is <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu4" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=2256" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 4)" >regular</a> and <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu3" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=5926" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 3)" >weakly cancellative</a>.

A simple semigroup (without zero) is completely simple if and only if it is <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu2" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=1534" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 2)" >completely regular</a>.

A 0 -simple semigroup is completely 0 -simple if and only if it is <a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu1" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=78" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 1)" >group</a>-<a class="PlanetMath nndropdown" id="menu0" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=450" onClick="return clickreturnvalue()" onMouseover="dropdown(this, 0)" >bound</a>.
